If you'd like a colourful hedge, there are several plants that will meet this need and grow into a sturdy hedge offering privacy:
Try grevillea for a hedge. This has a range of differently coloured flowers to choose from. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Use-Australian-Native-Plants-to-Grow-a-Hedge-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Use-Australian-Native-Plants-to-Grow-a-Hedge-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/7f/Use-Australian-Native-Plants-to-Grow-a-Hedge-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/aid1215226-v4-728px-Use-Australian-Native-Plants-to-Grow-a-Hedge-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
